    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-09-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-09-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="108"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                <head>108. Note From the United States to the Soviet Union<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d108fn1">Source: Ford Library, National Security Adviser, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> Reports on <gloss
                            target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>, China, and Middle East Discussions, Box
                        1, <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> Memcons and Reports, September
                        18–21, 1975–Talks with <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>. No
                        classification marking. A handwritten note indicates that <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> was given this note on September
                        21 during his meeting with <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>
                        in New York; see <ref target="#d107fn2">footnote 2, Document
                        107</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1975-09-21">undated</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> proposes the following approach to resolve
                    the outstanding issues in the new agreement for the limitation of strategic
                    offense armaments.</p>
                <p>1. Regarding air launched cruise missiles, the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    proposes that they be limited as follows: (a) the development, testing, and
                    deployment of air-launched cruise missiles with ranges greater than 2500 <gloss
                        target="#t_km_1">km</gloss> will be banned; (b) each side will be permitted
                    no more than 300 heavy bombers armed with cruise missiles with a range between
                    600 and 2500 <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss>; (c) as proposed by the Soviet
                    side cruise missiles with ranges over 600 <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss>
                    will be banned on other aircraft.</p>
                <p>2. For the limitation of sea-based cruise missiles, the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> accepts the Soviet proposal to ban the deployment of sea-based
                    cruise missiles with a range over 600 except as noted below.</p>
                <p>3. The <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> proposes to ban the development,
                    deployment and testing of sea-based cruise missiles with a range greater than
                    2000 <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss>.</p>
                <p>4. As for the Soviet Backfire bomber the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    accepts the Soviet assurance that it is not intended for use as a heavy bomber.
                    With respect to systems in a hybrid category, such as the Backfire bomber,
                    sea-based cruise missiles with a range between 600 <gloss target="#t_km_1"
                        >km</gloss> and 2000 <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss> and the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> FB–111 bomber, we propose that they not be
                    counted in the ceiling of 2400, but that both sides would be limited to no more
                    than a total of 300 of such systems; for the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    this would include the FB–111 bomber and sea-based cruise missiles with a range
                    of between 600 and 2000 <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss> in <pb facs="0518"
                        n="489" xml:id="pg_489"/> any combination; for the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"
                        >USSR</gloss> any combination of Backfire aircraft and sea-based cruise
                    missiles with a range between 600 <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss> and 2000
                        <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss>.</p>
                <p>5. The <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> position on defining a heavy <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> remains as previously proposed.</p>
            </div>
